          "content": "Your friend's suggestion breaks down the adaptation into what you can reuse, what needs simplification, and what's entirely new. Let me explain each section:\n\n## What Carries Over Directly (60% of your work is done)\n\n**BM25F Algorithm** - The core ranking math stays identical. In your USMLE search, you weighted fields like `title(12x)` and `labels(12x)` to prioritize certain content. For recruitment, you'd do the same but with job-relevant fields:\n- `skills_must_have(15x)` - highest weight for required skills\n- `job_title(12x)` - job titles matter a lot\n- `skills_nice_to_have(8x)` - bonus skills\n- `domain(6x)` - industry experience\n- `responsibilities(3x)` - lower weight for descriptions\n\n**Fuzzy Matching** - Your Damerau-Levenshtein implementation handles typos/variations. Critical for recruitment because:\n- \"Javascript\" vs \"JavaScript\" \n- \"Postgres\" vs \"PostgreSQL\"\n- \"ML\" vs \"Machine Learning\"\n\n**LRU Caching** - Your 64-entry cache system works identically for recruitment searches.\n\n**Prefix Matching** - Your binary search for autocomplete transfers directly to skill/title suggestions.\n\n## What's Different/Simpler\n\n**Synonym Dictionary** - Your USMLE engine has 197 synonym groups + 450 medical abbreviations (the hardest domain work). For recruitment, you need similar but smaller:\n```javascript\n{\n  \"ML\": [\"machine learning\", \"AI\", \"artificial intelligence\"],\n  \"JS\": [\"javascript\", \"node.js\", \"nodejs\"],\n  \"k8s\": [\"kubernetes\"]\n}\n```\nMaybe 80-100 tech abbreviations instead of 450 medical terms.\n\n**Intent Detection** - Your USMLE engine detects complex intents like \"brutal\", \"HY\", \"Step 2\". For recruitment it's simpler:\n- \"senior\" → filter `experience_years >= 5`\n- \"remote\" → filter `location = remote`\n- \"fintech\" → boost `domain = fintech`\n\n## What's Entirely New (No USMLE Equivalent)\n\n**Two-Dimensional Scoring** - This is the key difference:\n```\nUSMLE:     query → single relevance score → ranked list\nRecruiter: JD → Match Score (search) + Interest Score (LLM chat) → 2D ranking\n```\n\nYour USMLE engine only had one score axis. The recruitment system needs:\n1. **Match Score** - how well skills/experience align (your search engine)\n2. **Interest Score** - how engaged the candidate is (from LLM conversation)\n\n**Semantic/Vector Layer** - Your USMLE engine is purely lexical (BM25 + fuzzy + synonyms). Recruitment needs semantic understanding because:\n- Candidate: \"built distributed payment infrastructure\"\n- JD: \"microservices and fintech experience\"\n- Zero keyword overlap, but semantically identical\n\nMedical terms are precise (\"myocardial infarction\" = \"myocardial infarction\"), but job descriptions use varied language.\n\n## Recommended Architecture\n\n```\nLayer 1 (Lexical):   BM25F + Fuzzy from your USMLE engine\nLayer 2 (Semantic):  Embeddings (OpenAI/sentence-transformers)\nLayer 3 (Fusion):    score = 0.4 × BM25 + 0.6 × cosine_similarity\nLayer 4 (Re-rank):   LLM explains top 10-15 matches\n```\n\nYour existing engine covers Layer 1 almost completely.\n\n## Effort Breakdown\n\n- **Port BM25F + Fuzzy**: Low effort - mostly changing field weights\n- **Tech synonym dictionary**: Medium - 1-2 hours of data collection\n- **Add vector embeddings**: Medium - integrate OpenAI API + cosine similarity\n- **Score fusion**: Low - simple weighted average\n- **LLM re-ranking**: Medium - prompt engineering for explanations\n\n**Bottom line**: You're starting from 60% complete, not zero. Your USMLE search engine gives you a significant head start on the lexical matching layer."
